Initial  <URL>wind radar</URL> images showed very weak <URL>wind radar</URL>s associated with the system, and <URL>radar reflectivity mean values</URL> suggested a 0800 UTC shell within the center of the developing system. However, continued <URL>radar reflectivity analysis</URL> and <URL>satellite imagery</URL> suggested that a more typical tropical cyclone was forming, with <URL>radar-estimated minimum central pressure</URL> of about 1004 hPa (hPa<SUB>-</SUB>10 millibar) and a rapid strengthening seen in <URL>AWD</URL> (Automated Weather Data) and <URL>NOAA-AVN</URL> data. A flight of the <URL>P-3H</URL> (Hydroplane-3 Hercules) of <URL>JMA</URL> (Japan Meteorological Agency) confirmed the rapid development of <URL>Pamela</URL> as a tropical cyclone on October 21st, with maximum winds estimated to be around 45 knots (83 km/h) and a minimum central pressure of about 999 hPa (hPa<SUB>-</SUB>99 millibar).
